{{Infobox deity
|NAME = <hiero>N36:N35-M12</hiero><br/>Merencha<br/>''Mr-n-ḫ3''
|NAME-ERWEITERT = {{ill|New Kingdom|ja|新王国|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}
}}

'''Merencha''' (also written '''Mer-en-cha''') is, in {{ill|Egyptian Mythology|ja|エジプト神話|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the name of the winding watercourse that, in the land of {{ill|Ta-djeser|ja|タ＝デジェル|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, encloses the regions of {{ill|Aaru|ja|セシェト・イアル|de|Sechet-iaru|lt=Sechet-iaru|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sechet-hetep|ja|セシェト・ヘテプ|de|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Sechet-tjau|ja|セシェト・チャウ|de|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} located in the {{ill|Duat|ja|ドゥアト|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Merencha represents, as a likely equivalence of the {{ill|Lake of fire|ja|フレームレイク|lt=Flame|lt_ja=フラメン-|de|Flammensee|es|Lago de fuego|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|Knife Lake|ja|ナイフ湖|de|Messersee|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the realm of {{ill|Reincarnation|ja|転生|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Sun God|ja|太陽神|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Ra|ja|レ|lt=Ra|lt_ja=レ|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and of the deceased.

From an inscription accompanying the text passage of the {{ill|Book of the Dead|ja|エジプト死者の書|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, which gave its name to the region of Sechet-Tjau in the {{ill|Late Period (Egypt)|ja|エジプト後期|lt=Late Period|lt_ja=後期|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, it can be inferred that the inhabitants of Sechet-Iaru are capable, like Re at the birthplace of the gods, of performing a {{ill|Sunrise|ja|日の出|lt=Sunrise|lt_ja=日の出|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and sunset.

After qualification, the deceased can partake in the daily earthly journey of the Sun God; simultaneously, after his reincarnation, he can move freely in the water of Merencha throughout the Duat as well as on {{ill|Earth|ja|地球|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Literature ==
* {{ill|Rolf Krauss|ja|ロルフ・クラウス|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}: ''Astronomical Concepts and Afterlife Beliefs in the Pyramid Texts.'' Harrassowitz, Wiesbaden 1997, ISBN 3-447-03979-5.
* {{ill|Bertha Porter|ja|バーサ・ポーター|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ethel W. Burney, {{ill|Rosalind L.B. Moss|ja|ロザリンド・モス|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}: ''Topographical Bibliography of Ancient Egyptian Hieroglyphic Texts, Reliefs, and Paintings. Vol. 1, The Theban Necropolis. Part 1, Private Tombs.'' Griffith Institute, Oxford 1994, ISBN 0-900416-15-7.
